Environment-climate: For a European New Deal
BRUSSELS – As in European capitals, the "Green New Deal" is on everyone's lips, echoing the visionary economic program launched by President Franklin D. Roosevelt in 1933.
But this time, it's about the environment and climate.
And Europe is the continent where we can and must act.
The EU's commitment to these issues is not new: we have had a common program since 1972.
In 2005, the EU established the first emissions trading system, which remains the world's largest CO2 market.
And in 2015, the EU played a leading role in negotiating the Paris Agreement, committing to reduce its own greenhouse gas emissions by 40% (based on 1990 levels).
But these measures, despite their importance, are not sufficient to address the challenges facing today's world.
Increasing temperatures could lead to the complete disappearance of the Arctic ice cap by 2050.
Bees and many other insects are dying out, while microplastic pollution is ubiquitous in our environment.
And the number of victims of respiratory diseases is increasing as air pollution worsens.
We still have reasons to remain optimistic.
Let's see these people, growing in numbers every day, ready to act to challenge their lifestyles. Like these students and entire families descending in the streets of Stockholm, Prague, Brussels, and Milan every Thursdays!
Companies are also getting involved, seeing the unparalleled economic potential of a green economy.
But it is the national and European policymakers who too often lack ambition.
We have a window of opportunity to act. Let's seize it!
And let making Europe green our top political priority for the years to come, focused on three fronts.
First, Europe must become a carbon-neutral economy by 2050.
If we want to limit global warming to 1.5°C, we have no other choice: the EU's net emissions of carbon dioxide must be brought to zero by mid-century.
Together, we can invest massively in the future of our mobility, energy-efficient buildings and renewable energies, as well as in key technologies such as hydrogen batteries, new generations of solar panels, and green chemistry.
Together, we also need to apply strict CO2 emission limits to new private cars, public transportation, as well as commercial maritime and air transport.
And, working closely with our automotive industry, we can make Europe the first continent of electric vehicles by 2030.
Second, Europe must play a leading role in responsible resource use and become a genuine circular economy that minimizes waste.
Every year, 8 billion tons of materials are transformed into energy or products in the European Union.
But only 0.6 billion tons come from recycling.
We must do much better, which will require us to focus on four aspects: food waste and bioeconomy, textiles, construction, and rapidly evolving consumer goods.
Let us get to work right away, by launching, for example, a European initiative to combat planned obsolescence of household appliances and electronics, and by eliminating plastics from our value chains.
Thirdly, we must do much more to protect biodiversity.
According to the WWF, wildlife populations have decreased by about 60% worldwide since 1970.
The United Nations biodiversity conference, which will take place in Beijing next year, will be decisive.
Once again, the EU must show the way.
We must strengthen EU legislation on species protection and put forward an ambitious plan for the blue economy and the preservation of our seas.
We must also launch a genuine debate with our farmers (not against them!) on revising our standards and modernizing the common agricultural policy to accompany this green transition.
But these colossal tasks that lie ahead, we will not be able to accomplish them if they are always the same – and the most vulnerable – who are asked to bear their costs.
All proposed measures must therefore above all be designed to minimize social costs.
And at the same time, we must work with our partners today for international cooperation, combating unfair competition.
Because it serves no purpose to have strict European regulations on pesticides or forest management if our imported foods and wood are produced without respecting sustainability criteria.
These three initiatives could become the pillars of a Sustainability Pact at the heart of the EU's new political cycle.
Because we are in a state of acute ecological debt, and it would be more than justified for the stability and growth pact that applies to the public finances of member states to find an equivalent for green objectives of a green Europe!
To achieve its goals, this Sustainability Pact will require coordinated action across all domains: climate, trade, taxation, agriculture, and innovation.
The EU should not hesitate to use its regulatory powers, for example: expanding the scope of eco-design legislation and the "extended producer responsibility" for products placed on the market could significantly boost environmental innovation.
Massive investments will also be necessary.
The European Commission estimates that the EU will need an additional 180 billion euros in annual investments to meet its commitments under the Paris Agreement.
This is a achievable goal.
The European Investment Bank is already the largest multilateral provider of climate-focused funds.
And the EU's new budget and its investment plan, leveraging private sector investments, could further strengthen the Union's power to act.
The financial sector must play a fundamental role: through climate-related disclosure of financial information, we can encourage the world's largest financial institutions, such as Norway's sovereign wealth fund and BlackRock, to adopt a longer-term vision and avoid what Bank of England governor Mark Carney called the "horizon tragedy."
Finally, while some member states may see this as a risky project, we must have a debate on taxation, but also on subsidies applicable to fossil fuels. In short, about integrating sustainability into public spending.
Behind these initiatives, these projects, the key lies in the method. For this "Green New Deal" to bear fruit, we must define ambitious objectives and short- and long-term "missions" that resonate socially.
With member states and the European Parliament, we will need to determine a common roadmap and conduct in-depth discussions, just as with our regions, cities, businesses, trade unions, and civil society.
None of this can be done overnight.
But we can no longer close our eyes and hold our breath to avoid the reality of our environment.
It is already very late to launch a European "Green New Deal." But it is not too late.
Let us not miss this new opportunity!
